ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, metal-free nitrogen-doped carbon nanodots (N-CNDs) with excellent enzymatic activity and antibacterial properties were innovatively fabricated from tea polyphenols and ethylenediamine (Scheme 1
                     ). N-CNDs exhibited excellent catalytic activity under the trigger of a specific light source, which can simulate the catalytic behavior of oxidases and oxidize 3,3′,5,5′-tetramethylbenzidine (TMB) to blue oxidized TMB (ox-TMB). The catalytic process of N-CNDs was mediated by superoxide radicals (•O2
                     −) generated by oxygen activation with a maximum reaction rate (Vmax) of 1.59 μM⋅s−1 and a Michaelis constant (Km) of 0.421 mM. Furthermore, N-CNDs inherited the inherent antibacterial properties of tea polyphenols and combined with light-driven enzyme-like activation to exhibit significant inhibition against Gram-positive Staphylococcus aureus (S. aureus) and Bacillus subtilis (B. subtilis), as well as Gram-negative Escherichia coli (E. coli) and Proteus mirabilis (P. vulgaris). More interestingly, the unique oxidase-mimicking activity of N-CNDs can effectively enhance their inherent antibacterial properties, showing great potential as a promising antibacterial agent.

Unexpectedly, we found that the prepared N-CNDs show oxidase-mimicking activity under light excitation using TMB as a typical substrate. As shown in Fig. 2
                        a, under irradiation with a 500 W mercury-xenon lamp loaded with 365 nm filter (20 mW‧cm−2), N-CNDs can catalyze the rapid oxidation of TMB to produce blue products, giving a strong characteristic absorbance at 652 nm. Similar to natural oxidases, the pH of the buffer, the enzyme dose, and the illumination time may affect the oxidase-mimicking activity of N-CNDs. As seen from Fig. 2b, at pH 3.5, the absorbance of ox-TMB was maximum at 652 nm, so 3.5 was chosen as the optimal pH for all subsequent experiments. The absorbance of the blue substance produced by TMB oxidation at 652 nm increased with increasing dose of N-CNDs (Fig. 2c), indicating that the oxidation of TMB by N-CNDs was dose-dependent. Finally, considering the detection sensitivity and analysis speed, the optimal conditions were determined to be 100 μg⋅mL−1 N-CNDs, 80 μM TMB, and pH = 3.5. As presented in Fig. 2d, N-CNDs exhibited a stepwise oxidase-mimicking activity under alternating on-off irradiation of a specific light source, demonstrating their light-controlled catalytic activity. The light-controlled catalytic activity may be attributed to the nitrogen atoms enhancing the electron charge transfer and specific surface area of the nanoparticles, thus providing the catalytic active sites (Wang et al., 2021b). It can be observed that the kinetics of N-CNDs as a mimic oxidase fits the typical Michaelis-Menten equation well within the tested concentration range (Fig. 2e). Lineweaver-Burk model was established according to Michaelis-Menten kinetic equation, and the characteristic parameters Km and Vmax of enzyme kinetics at pH = 3.5 were 0.421 mM and 1.59 μM⋅s−1, respectively (Fig. 2f). When the enzymatic reaction reaches half of Vmax, Km equals [S], which means that smaller Km values require less substrate to reach the maximum velocity and a greater affinity between enzyme and substrate (Gao et al., 2007; Zhu et al., 2020). Furthermore, we tabulated the kinetic characteristic parameters of this work compared with other types of carbon nanodots-based nanozymes (Table 1
                        ). Most of the reported carbon nanodots-based nanozymes possess peroxidase-like activity, which is mainly dependent on the stimulation of H2O2 production of ROS by carbon nanodots (Kitchawengkul et al., 2021; Lee et al., 2021; Li et al., 2020; Wang et al., 2022). Compared with TA-NCDs (Wang et al., 2021b), a carbon nanodots-based nanozyme with light-driven oxidase-like activity, N-CNDs have better kinetic constants Vmax and Km and display excellent catalytic performance.

Since N-CNDs carry relatively weak antibacterial effects on their own and have limitations in practical applications, we further explored whether the oxidase-mimicking activity of N-CNDs can enhance their own antibacterial behavior. Firstly, live/dead bacterial viability was detected by AO/PI co-staining of untreated, N-CNDs-treated, and N-CNDs + light-treated bacteria. With the help of confocal fluorescence microscope imaging analysis, the distribution of live and dead bacteria was visualized intuitively. After staining, live bacteria display a green fluorescent signal, while dead bacteria exhibit a red fluorescent signal due to membrane damage. More S. aureus and E. coli exhibited red fluorescence in the N-CNDs-treated and N-CNDs + light-treated groups compared to the strong green fluorescence signal in the control group. Moreover, the red fluorescence signal in the N-CNDs + light-treated group was significantly stronger than that in the N-CNDs-treated group, while the green fluorescence signal almost disappeared (Fig. 6
                        a). These results further confirmed that light can enhance the antibacterial efficiency of N-CNDs. Subsequently, in order to better explore the relationship between the antibacterial ability of N-CNDs in vitro and the duration of light exposure, bacterial suspensions were incubated with N-CNDs solution for 3 h and then subjected to different lengths of light exposure and counted by the plate method (Fig. 6b and c). As can be seen in Fig. 6d and e, in the absence of N-CNDs, S. aureus and E. coli exhibited 97.5% bacterial viability after 60 min of light irradiation, suggesting that light has little effect on the viabilities of S. aureus and E. coli. In the absence of light, the bacterial viabilities of S. aureus and E. coli gradually decreased with increasing concentrations of N-CNDs, which was consistent with the results of previous experiments. The survival viabilities of S. aureus and E. coli decreased accordingly with increasing concentration of N-CNDs, which was consistent with previous studies. After 60 min of light irradiation, 9.6 μg⋅mL−1 of N-CNDs can inactivate 98.01% of E. coli and 81.12% of S. aureus, respectively. For E. coli, when the concentration of N-CNDs reached 14.4 μg⋅mL−1, almost no colonies were found on solid agar plates after 60 min of light irradiation. Additionally, a two-way ANOVA revealed that both N-CNDs concentration (p < 0.001) and light duration (p < 0.01) had significant negative effects on bacterial viability (Table 2
                        ). Meanwhile, the concentration of N-CNDs and the duration of light had an interactive effect on bacterial viability (p < 0.05, Table 2), evidencing that the concentration of N-CNDs and the duration of light have a synergistic effect on antibacterial activity, a conclusion that applies to both S. aureus and E. coli. Taken together, combining the destructive behavior of N-CNDs on bacterial membranes with the production of ROS by light irradiation of N-CNDs can accelerate bacterial death and improve antibacterial efficiency (Fig. 7
                        ), illustrating that N-CNDs have considerable potential for treating bacterial infections in vivo or inhibiting bacteria in the environment.
